  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or other crimes) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nGovernments and international organizations have established strict legal frameworks to combat money laundering because it undermines financial systems, facilitates criminal activities, and has broader negative impacts on economies and societies. Key international agreements, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** recommendations, provide global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. Most countries have enacted laws and regulations to criminalize money laundering and require financial institutions to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is widely and unequivocally considered illegal across the globe.",
